======================================================================
PART 1: dim/rank FOR ALL EXCEPTIONAL LIE GROUPS
======================================================================

  Type   rank   dim     h   dim/rank  as fraction    corner?
  -----------------------------------------------------------------
  G₂        2    14     6     7.0000            7          —
  F₄        4    52    12    13.0000           13          —
  E₆        6    78    12    13.0000           13          —
  E₇        7   133    18    19.0000           19    3^3-2^3
  E₈        8   248    30    31.0000           31          —

  Corner piece sequence 3ⁿ-2ⁿ: 0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059, ...

  MATCHES:
    dim(G₂)/rank(G₂) = 14/2 = 7 = 2²+3 = KEY₁²+KEY₂
    dim(F₄)/rank(F₄) = 52/4 = 13 = KEY₁²+KEY₂²
    dim(E₆)/rank(E₆) = 78/6 = 13 = KEY₁²+KEY₂²
    dim(E₇)/rank(E₇) = 133/7 = 19 = 3³-2³ = KEY₂³-KEY₁³ ✓
    dim(E₈)/rank(E₈) = 248/8 = 31 = 2⁵-1 = KEY₁^5-1

  ALL dim/rank ratios in terms of (2,3):
     7 = 2²+3¹   = KEY₁² + KEY₂
    13 = 2²+3²   = KEY₁² + KEY₂² (appears TWICE)
    19 = 3³-2³   = KEY₂³ - KEY₁³ (corner piece n=3)
    31 = 2⁵-1    = KEY₁^(KEY₁+KEY₂) - 1 (Mersenne)

  DEEPER PATTERNS:
     7 = 2³-1    (Mersenne prime, M₃)
    13 = 2⁴-3    (power of 2 minus KEY₂)
    19 = 2⁵-13   ... no. 19 = 3³-2³ better
    31 = 2⁵-1    (Mersenne prime, M₅)

  As a^i ± b^j where {a,b} ⊆ {2,3}:
      7 = 2^3-2^0, 2^2+3^1, 2^3-3^0, 2^4-3^2, 3^1+2^2
     13 = 2^2+3^2, 2^4-3^1, 3^2+2^2
     19 = 2^4+3^1, 3^1+2^4, 3^3-2^3
     31 = 2^5-2^0, 2^2+3^3, 2^5-3^0, 3^3+2^2

======================================================================
PART 2: THE (2,3) RECURRENCE AT dim/rank
======================================================================

  Can we find A,B such that A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ = dim/rank for n=1,...?

  For each pair of consecutive values, solve A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ:
    n=(1,2) for (7,13): A=4, B=-1/3, seq=[7, 13, 23, 37, 47, 13], hits=2
    n=(1,2) for (7,19): A=1, B=5/3, seq=[7, 19, 53, 151, 437, 1279], hits=2
    n=(1,2) for (7,31): A=-5, B=17/3, seq=[7, 31, 113, 379, 1217, 3811], hits=2
    n=(1,2) for (13,19): A=10, B=-7/3, seq=[13, 19, 17, -29, -247, -1061], hits=2
    n=(1,2) for (13,31): A=4, B=5/3, seq=[13, 31, 77, 199, 533, 1471], hits=2
    n=(1,2) for (19,31): A=13, B=-7/3, seq=[19, 31, 41, 19, -151, -869], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (7,13): A=5, B=-1, seq=[7, 11, 13, -1, -83, -409], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (7,19): A=22/5, B=-3/5, seq=[7, 12, 19, 21, -5, -155], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (7,31): A=16/5, B=1/5, seq=[7, 14, 31, 67, 151, 350], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (13,19): A=49/5, B=-11/5, seq=[13, 19, 19, -21, -221, -976], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (13,31): A=43/5, B=-7/5, seq=[13, 21, 31, 24, -65, -470], hits=2
    n=(1,3) for (19,31): A=14, B=-3, seq=[19, 29, 31, -19, -281, -1291], hits=2
    n=(2,4) for (7,13): A=5/2, B=-1/3, seq=[4, 7, 11, 13, -1, -83], hits=2
    n=(2,4) for (7,19): A=11/5, B=-1/5, seq=[3, 7, 12, 19, 21, -5], hits=2
    n=(2,4) for (19,31): A=7, B=-1, seq=[11, 19, 29, 31, -19, -281], hits=2
    n=(3,5) for (19,31): A=7/2, B=-1/3, seq=[6, 11, 19, 29, 31, -19], hits=2

  Direct check against 3ⁿ-2ⁿ:
    n=1: 3^1-2^1 = 1
    n=2: 3^2-2^2 = 5
    n=3: 3^3-2^3 = 19 ← dim/rank!
    n=4: 3^4-2^4 = 65
    n=5: 3^5-2^5 = 211
    n=6: 3^6-2^6 = 665
    n=7: 3^7-2^7 = 2059
    n=8: 3^8-2^8 = 6305
    n=9: 3^9-2^9 = 19171

  Only 19 = 3³-2³ matches.

  Direct check against 2ⁿ-1 (Mersenne):
    n=1: 2^1-1 = 1
    n=2: 2^2-1 = 3
    n=3: 2^3-1 = 7 ← dim/rank!
    n=4: 2^4-1 = 15
    n=5: 2^5-1 = 31 ← dim/rank!
    n=6: 2^6-1 = 63
    n=7: 2^7-1 = 127
    n=8: 2^8-1 = 255
    n=9: 2^9-1 = 511

  7 = 2³-1 (M₃) and 31 = 2⁵-1 (M₅) match.
  Both are Mersenne PRIMES!

  Direct check against KEY₁ⁿ+KEY₂ⁿ = 2ⁿ+3ⁿ:
    n=0: 2^0+3^0 = 2
    n=1: 2^1+3^1 = 5
    n=2: 2^2+3^2 = 13 ← dim/rank!
    n=3: 2^3+3^3 = 35
    n=4: 2^4+3^4 = 97
    n=5: 2^5+3^5 = 275
    n=6: 2^6+3^6 = 793
    n=7: 2^7+3^7 = 2315

  13 = 2²+3² matches! (for both F₄ and E₆)

======================================================================
PART 3: UNIFIED FORMULA — dim/rank AND THE KEYS
======================================================================

  FORMULA CANDIDATES:

  dim/rank = 2^a ± 3^c form:
    G₂:  7 = 2³ - 3⁰ = 8-1
    F₄: 13 = 2² + 3² = 4+9
    E₆: 13 = 2² + 3² = 4+9
    E₇: 19 = -2³ + 3³ = -8+27
    E₈: 31 = 2⁵ - 3⁰ = 32-1

  Exponents in 2^a ± 3^c:
    G₂: (3,0) with sign -
    F₄: (2,2) with sign +
    E₆: (2,2) with sign +
    E₇: (3,3) with sign +  (reading as 3³-2³)
    E₈: (5,0) with sign -

  The exponents: (3,0), (2,2), (2,2), (3,3), (5,0)
  For G₂ and E₈: second exponent is 0 (pure Mersenne)
  For F₄ and E₆: equal exponents (sum of equal powers)
  For E₇: equal exponents 3 (difference of equal powers)

  The first exponents: 3, 2, 2, 3, 5
  = KEY₂, KEY₁, KEY₁, KEY₂, KEY₁+KEY₂ !

  dim - rank = number of positive + negative roots:
    G₂: dim-rank = 14-2 = 12 = 2·6 positive roots
    F₄: dim-rank = 52-4 = 48 = 2·24 positive roots
    E₆: dim-rank = 78-6 = 72 = 2·36 positive roots
    E₇: dim-rank = 133-7 = 126 = 2·63 positive roots
    E₈: dim-rank = 248-8 = 240 = 2·120 positive roots

  Number of POSITIVE roots:
    G₂: 6 positive roots = rank·(dim/rank - 1)/2 = 2·3
    F₄: 24 positive roots = rank·(dim/rank - 1)/2 = 4·6
    E₆: 36 positive roots = rank·(dim/rank - 1)/2 = 6·6
    E₇: 63 positive roots = rank·(dim/rank - 1)/2 = 7·9
    E₈: 120 positive roots = rank·(dim/rank - 1)/2 = 8·15

  Checking: dim = rank · h + something?
    G₂: rank·h = 2·6 = 12, dim = 14, diff = 2
    F₄: rank·h = 4·12 = 48, dim = 52, diff = 4
    E₆: rank·h = 6·12 = 72, dim = 78, diff = 6
    E₇: rank·h = 7·18 = 126, dim = 133, diff = 7
    E₈: rank·h = 8·30 = 240, dim = 248, diff = 8

  None of them has dim = rank·h exactly.
  But: dim = rank·(h-1) + rank + something?
    G₂: rank·(h-1) = 2·5 = 10, dim-rank·(h-1) = 4
    F₄: rank·(h-1) = 4·11 = 44, dim-rank·(h-1) = 8
    E₆: rank·(h-1) = 6·11 = 66, dim-rank·(h-1) = 12
    E₇: rank·(h-1) = 7·17 = 119, dim-rank·(h-1) = 14
    E₈: rank·(h-1) = 8·29 = 232, dim-rank·(h-1) = 16

  Number of positive roots = dim/rank formula:
  For type X_r: #Φ⁺ = (dim-rank)/2
    G₂: #Φ⁺ = 6, r·h/2 = 6 ✓
    F₄: #Φ⁺ = 24, r·h/2 = 24 ✓
    E₆: #Φ⁺ = 36, r·h/2 = 36 ✓
    E₇: #Φ⁺ = 63, r·h/2 = 63 ✓
    E₈: #Φ⁺ = 120, r·h/2 = 120 ✓

  YES! #Φ⁺ = r·h/2 always.
  Therefore: dim = rank + 2·(rank·h/2) = rank·(h+1)
  Wait: dim = rank + rank·h = rank·(1+h)?
    G₂: rank·(h+1) = 2·7 = 14, dim = 14 ✓
    F₄: rank·(h+1) = 4·13 = 52, dim = 52 ✓
    E₆: rank·(h+1) = 6·13 = 78, dim = 78 ✓
    E₇: rank·(h+1) = 7·19 = 133, dim = 133 ✓
    E₈: rank·(h+1) = 8·31 = 248, dim = 248 ✓

  WRONG. dim ≠ rank·(h+1) in general.
  The correct formula: dim = rank + r·h = rank·(1+h)... no wait
  dim = rank + |Φ| = rank + r·h
  But |Φ| = 2·|Φ⁺| = 2·(r·h/2) = r·h
    G₂: rank + rank·h = 2 + 12 = 14, dim = 14 ✓
    F₄: rank + rank·h = 4 + 48 = 52, dim = 52 ✓
    E₆: rank + rank·h = 6 + 72 = 78, dim = 78 ✓
    E₇: rank + rank·h = 7 + 126 = 133, dim = 133 ✓
    E₈: rank + rank·h = 8 + 240 = 248, dim = 248 ✓

  So dim = rank·(1 + h) FOR ALL SIMPLE LIE ALGEBRAS!
  This means: dim/rank = h + 1

    G₂: dim/rank = 7 = h+1 = 6+1 = 7 ✓
    F₄: dim/rank = 13 = h+1 = 12+1 = 13 ✓
    E₆: dim/rank = 13 = h+1 = 12+1 = 13 ✓
    E₇: dim/rank = 19 = h+1 = 18+1 = 19 ✓
    E₈: dim/rank = 31 = h+1 = 30+1 = 31 ✓

  WAIT: dim/rank should be h+1?
    G₂: 14/2 = 7, h+1 = 7 ✓
    F₄: 52/4 = 13, h+1 = 13 ✓
    E₆: 78/6 = 13, h+1 = 13 ✓
    E₇: 133/7 = 19, h+1 = 19 ✓
    E₈: 248/8 = 31, h+1 = 31 ✓

  YES!!! dim/rank = h+1 FOR ALL EXCEPTIONAL LIE GROUPS!
  This is because dim = rank + |Φ| = rank + rank·h = rank·(h+1)

======================================================================
PART 4: THE h+1 VALUES AND (2,3) EXPRESSIONS
======================================================================

  The Coxeter numbers plus 1:
    G₂: h+1 = 7 = 2^2+3^1, 2^3-2^0, 2^3-3^0
    F₄: h+1 = 13 = 2^2+3^2, 2^4-3^1, 3^2+2^2
    E₆: h+1 = 13 = 2^2+3^2, 2^4-3^1, 3^2+2^2
    E₇: h+1 = 19 = 2^4+3^1, 3^1+2^4, 3^3-2^3
    E₈: h+1 = 31 = 2^2+3^3, 2^5-2^0, 2^5-3^0

  So the real question is: what are the h-values?
  h(G₂) = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂
  h(F₄) = 12 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  h(E₆) = 12 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  h(E₇) = 18 = KEY₁·KEY₂²
  h(E₈) = 30 = KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)

  h-values in KEY₁^a · KEY₂^b · (KEY₁+KEY₂)^c form:
    h(G₂) = 6  = 2¹·3¹ → (a,b,c) = (1,1,0)
    h(F₄) = 12 = 2²·3¹ → (a,b,c) = (2,1,0)
    h(E₆) = 12 = 2²·3¹ → (a,b,c) = (2,1,0)
    h(E₇) = 18 = 2¹·3² → (a,b,c) = (1,2,0)
    h(E₈) = 30 = 2¹·3¹·5¹ → (a,b,c) = (1,1,1)

  BEAUTIFUL: E₈ is the ONLY one that needs KEY₁+KEY₂ = 5
  G₂, F₄, E₆ use only KEY₁ and KEY₂
  E₇ uses KEY₁¹·KEY₂² (more KEY₂ than KEY₁)
  E₈ uses all three: KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)

  dim = rank · (h+1):
    dim(G₂) = 2·7 = 14
      rank = 2, h+1 = 7
    dim(F₄) = 4·13 = 52
      rank = 4, h+1 = 13
    dim(E₆) = 6·13 = 78
      rank = 6, h+1 = 13
    dim(E₇) = 7·19 = 133
      rank = 7, h+1 = 19 = 3^3-2^3
    dim(E₈) = 8·31 = 248
      rank = 8, h+1 = 31

  FOR G₂: h+1 = 7 = 2³-1 = 2^rank+1 - 1 (rank=2, so 2^3-1) ✓
  FOR E₈: h+1 = 31 = 2⁵-1 = 2^rank-3 - 1 (rank=8, so 2^5-1) ✓
  Both G₂ and E₈ have h+1 = Mersenne prime!

  THE FINAL CONNECTION:
  dim(E₇)/rank(E₇) = 19 = 3³-2³ = h(E₇)+1
  This is TRIVIALLY TRUE because dim/rank = h+1 always!
  But the INTERESTING fact is that h(E₇)+1 = 19 = 3³-2³
  i.e., h(E₇) = 18 = 3³-2³-1 = 27-8-1
  Or equivalently: h(E₇) = KEY₂³ - KEY₁³ - 1

  Which h values are related to 3ⁿ-2ⁿ?
    h(G₂)-1 = 5 = 3^2-2^2
    h(E₇)+1 = 19 = 3^3-2^3

======================================================================
PART 5: THE CLASSICAL LIE ALGEBRAS — SAME FORMULA
======================================================================

  Type         rank  dim   h dim/rank  h+1 match
  A₁=B₁=C₁        1    3   2        3    3     ✓
  A₂              2    8   3        4    4     ✓
  B₂=C₂           2   10   4        5    5     ✓
  A₃=D₃           3   15   4        5    5     ✓
  B₃              3   21   6        7    7     ✓
  C₃              3   21   6        7    7     ✓
  A₄              4   24   5        6    6     ✓
  B₄              4   36   8        9    9     ✓
  C₄              4   36   8        9    9     ✓
  D₄              4   28   6        7    7     ✓
  A₅              5   35   6        7    7     ✓
  D₅              5   45   8        9    9     ✓

  dim/rank = h+1 holds for ALL simple Lie algebras!
  This is the well-known formula: dim(g) = rank(g)·(h(g)+1)
  derived from dim(g) = rank(g) + |Φ| = rank(g) + rank(g)·h(g)

  Where |Φ| = rank·h comes from the fact that the
  average squared root length times rank gives |Φ|·h... 
  Actually: |Φ| = rank·h is well-known for simply-laced types
  and extends to all types with appropriate normalization.

======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

The dim/rank = h+1 identity means the 'corner piece' connection
is really about Coxeter numbers:

  h(G₂) + 1 = 7 = 2³-1 (Mersenne prime M₃)
  h(F₄) + 1 = 13 = 2²+3² (sum of key squares)
  h(E₆) + 1 = 13 = 2²+3² (same!)
  h(E₇) + 1 = 19 = 3³-2³ (corner piece at n=3)
  h(E₈) + 1 = 31 = 2⁵-1 (Mersenne prime M₅)

The Coxeter numbers themselves:
  h(G₂) = 6 = 2·3 = KEY₁·KEY₂
  h(F₄) = 12 = 4·3 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  h(E₆) = 12 = 4·3 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  h(E₇) = 18 = 2·9 = KEY₁·KEY₂²
  h(E₈) = 30 = 2·3·5 = KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)

The 2^a·3^b decomposition of h:
  G₂: 2¹3¹ → exponent vector (1,1)
  F₄: 2²3¹ → exponent vector (2,1)
  E₆: 2²3¹ → exponent vector (2,1)
  E₇: 2¹3² → exponent vector (1,2)
  E₈: 2¹3¹5¹ → needs the THIRD key

Pattern: exponent vectors (a,b) where h = 2^a · 3^b:
  G₂: (1,1) — balanced
  F₄ = E₆: (2,1) — KEY₁-heavy
  E₇: (1,2) — KEY₂-heavy
  E₈: needs 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ (transcends the two-key system)

  G₂ and E₈ are the BOOKENDS:
    G₂ starts with h = KEY₁·KEY₂ (the product)
    E₈ ends with h = KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂) (the full triple)
    Ratio: h(E₈)/h(G₂) = 30/6 = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂

  F₄/E₆ and E₇ are DUAL:
    h(F₄) = h(E₆) = 12 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
    h(E₇) = 18 = KEY₁·KEY₂²
    Ratio: h(E₇)/h(E₆) = 18/12 = 3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁
    This is the GOLDEN RATIO of the keys!
